Mocha French silk pie! The flavors of espresso with rich milk chocolate in a silky smooth pie. To celebrate the @KitchenAidUSA Pie-A-Polooza, I made this pie using  my favorite KitchenAidStand Mixer and the new Cordless Collection that is a true game changer. I am free of cords! My dream! #sponsored Thanks again to all who entered the Pie-A-Polooza giveaway and a special congrats to our lucky winner!
Whether you’re making this pie for the holiday season or just for fun, tag me in your creations with #MakeItTogether! #KitchenAidUSA The winner of the Giveaway is @ughnettie And here is the full list of ingredients:

Crust:
2 ¼ cups ginger snap crumbs (about 42 cookies)
Pinch kosher salt
½ cup unsalted butter, melted

Filling:
3 ounces milk chocolate, chopped
12 Tbsp unsalted butter (at room temp)
¾ cup granulated sugar
¼ tsp kosher salt
2 Tbsp coffee liqueur
1 tbls cooled espresso (OR 2 tbls strongly brewed coffee)
3 large cold eggs

Topping:
1 cup heavy whipping cream
1 Tbsp powdered sugar
Pinch kosher salt
Chocolate shavings

node.text:
grilled corn 🌽 with chipotle bourbon butter 🥃🌶🔥 and sprinkling of cotija on top. so good and SO easy. if you want more IGTV vids like this, leave suggestions on topics/recipes/how-tos below! here’s the recipe (it’s also on the blog if you want a printable recipe!): .
Chipotle Bourbon Butter: 
1/4 cup bourbon
1 teaspoon brown sugar
Pinch of kosher salt 
1/2 cup unsalted butter, at room temperature
1 chipotle in adobo 
1 garlic clove, peeled and roughly chopped 
Grilled Corn: 
5-6 ears of corn, husks pulled back
neutral oil (for grill)
As Garnish: 
1 ounce cotija cheese, crumbled
1 tablespoon minced cilantro 
To Make the Chipotle Bourbon Butter: 
To a small saucepan, set over medium heat, add the bourbon, brown sugar and pinch of salt. Bring to a gentle simmer and cook until reduced by half. Transfer to a food processor and allow to come to room temperature, about 10 minutes. 
When the bourbon mixture is cool, add the chipotles in adobo, butter and garlic clove. Pulse until combined, about 5 minutes. Scrape down the sides and make sure it's all combined. Place the butter to the center and roll it into a log, twisting the sides. Transfer to the fridge and keep up to 1 week. Or you can leave it out if using immediately. (I find it best to add room temperature butter to the corn.) To Make the Grilled Corn:
Preheat your grill for 10 minutes with the lid closed. When the grill is ready, brush the corn with oil on all sides. I peeled back the husks and tied them together using a strip of husk. 
Place the corn onto the grill and cover to cook for about 3 to 4 minutes. Check on the corn's doneness and if it needs more time, let it be. OR you can flip it to its opposite side. Cook for an additional 3 to 4 minutes. When the corn is toasted and lightly browned on all sides, remove the corn. 
To Assemble:
Plate the corn and top it with a few dollops of butter. Brush it on so it's a nice even layer and then sprinkle on some cotija. Finish with the cilantro. Repeat with the remaining corn.

node.text:
#ad espresso martinis are all the rage right now. for me, there was always something missing: ahh yes, something creamy and delicious. I’ve created my own recipe, made even better and creamier with @baileysus deliciously light. 🍸 ☕️ It has the same delicious flavor as the original but with 40% less sugar. It’s the perfect addition. yumm. 
 
Try it out over this long weekend and let me know what you think! 
 
Recipe for one Deliciously Light Espresso Martini: 
1.75 ounces @baileysus Deliciously Light
2 ounces vodka
1 ounce freshly brewed espresso (cooled down) 
coffee beans, for garnish

node.text:
Pumpkin spice tres leches for #hispanicheritagemonth x @Target. This is my favorite collab of American culture (pumpkin spice, hi!) and my favorite classic tres leches cake. It starts with a big haul from @Target for everything from the pan/supplies to groceries. A one-stop shop experience. And then top it with fluffy whipped cream and eat a slice. #MasQue #ad 

Wet Mix: 
4 large eggs, separated
1 cup white granulated sugar, divided
2/3 cup pure pumpkin puree 
1 teaspoon pure vanilla extract

Dry Mix: 
3/4 cup all-purpose flour
1 teaspoon baking powder
2 teaspoon pumpkin spice 
1/4 teaspoon salt

The three milks: 
1/2 cup whole milk
1 (14-ounce) can of sweetened condensed milk
1/2 cup light coconut milk or evaporated milk 
Whipped Cream, for topping
1/2 teaspoon pumpkin pie spice, for topping

1. Preheat the oven to 350 degrees. Grease a 9x13 cake pan.
2. Add egg whites and 1/2 cup sugar to the bowl of a stand-up mixer (with the whisk attachment) and beat until stiff peaks. Scoop it out and put it into another bowl. 
3. Place the bowl back on the stand-up mixer (no need to clean it out) and add the remaining 1/2 cup sugar and egg yolks. Beat until pale yellow and double in volume. Next, mix in the pumpkin puree and vanilla. 
4. Place a sieve atop the bowl on the stand-up mixer and sift in the flour, baking powder, pumpkin spice and salt. Mix until just combined. 
5. Fold in the egg whites until you no longer see any speckles of remaining egg white. 
6. Pour batter into pan and transfer to the oven to bake for 15 to 18 minutes, until a skewer when inserted into the center comes out clean. Let cool completely in the pan before proceeding with the rest of the recipe.
7. In a large measuring cup, add the coconut milk, whole milk and condensed milk. Whisk until combined. Using a skewer or fork, create little holes on the top of the cake. Pour the milk mixture over the cake (it may seem like a lot but it will absorb!). Transfer to the fridge to 2 to 3 hours, ideally overnight.
8. Just before serving, top the cake with fluffy whipped cream and dust with cinnamon or pumpkin pie spice. Slice and serve.

cheesy garlic bread 🧄 roasted garlic is the move--it adds a more subtle garlic flavor. mash it with some room temperature butter 🧈 and smother it on some crusty italian loaves of bread for a divine experience. here are the exact measurements:
1 head garlic
1 tsp olive oil
Kosher salt and freshly ground pepper
1/2 cup unsalted butter (4 ounces)
2 tbls minced italian parsley
1/4 tsp red pepper 1/2 cup (2 ounces) grated parmesan or grana padano
Italian bread (cuban bread would be good too!)

Sesame Tofu with Broccoli + Riced Cauliflower featuring @birdseyevegetables 🥦 
#sponsored My favorite quick, easy meal that can be made with frozen veggies, pantry staples and other ingredients we usually have stocked at home. Visit my bio to shop for recipe ingredients.  
 
8-ounce block extra-firm tofu  
2 teaspoons corn starch  
Kosher salt  
2 teaspoons avocado oil  
1/4 cup shoyu soy sauce  
2 tablespoons tahini
2 tablespoons sesame oil  
1 tablespoon rice wine vinegar 
2 teaspoons finely grated ginger  
2 garlic cloves  
1 (bag) Birds Eye Steamfresh Broccoli Florets 
1 (bag) Birds Eye Steamfresh Original Riced Cauliflower 
2 scallions, sliced  
 
1.  In a medium bowl, combine the tofu with corn starch and a few pinches of salt. In a pan, add the avocado oil. When it’s hot, add the tofu to the pan and cook until crispy, flipping after 1 to 2 minutes. Remove from the pan.  
2. In a small bowl, whisk together the soy sauce, sesame oil, tahini, rice wine vinegar, ginger and garlic. 
3. Separately cook Birds Eye frozen riced cauliflower + frozen broccoli per the instructions (I used my microwave to save time!)
4. Then, pour the Birds Eye frozen broccoli and riced cauliflower into the pan and cook for 1 to 2 minutes. Add the sesame oil mixture and cook until softened.  
5. Top with sesame seeds and lots of scallions
